Research the empirical validity of the Maintainability Index formula and its variants. The original Coleman et al. (1994) formula is: MI = 171 - 5.2 * ln(HV) - 0.23 * CC - 16.2 * ln(LOC) + 50 * sin(sqrt(2.4 * CM)), where HV is Halstead Volume, CC is cyclomatic complexity, LOC is lines of code, and CM is comment density. Document the original derivation and the dataset it was validated on. Then research Microsoft's modified version used in Visual Studio, which drops the comment term and rescales to 0-100. Find studies that have challenged the formula: Heitlager et al.'s work on the SIG Maintainability Model, the Riaz et al. (2009) systematic review, and Welker (2001) validation study. Research the Halstead complexity measures in depth: the four base counts (n1, n2, N1, N2), the derived measures (vocabulary, length, volume, difficulty, effort, time, bugs), and their empirical validation record. Document which components of the MI formula have the strongest independent predictive power when studied in isolation. Also research whether the MI formula performs differently across languages, particularly when applied to dynamically typed languages like Python versus statically typed languages like Java or Go. Include any proposed updated formulas from post-2010 research that improve on the original.
